1
00:00:00,404 --> 00:00:03,157
I'm going to tell you about my private life.

2
00:00:03,157 --> 00:00:07,184
I've had some good news recently, is that I've got…

3
00:00:07,184 --> 00:00:18,439
My wife has always had a dream, OK, to own a little place in the countryside, and it became my dream when she told me about it every day for ten years.

4
00:00:18,439 --> 00:00:28,838
And recently I bought a little place in the countryside for us, beautiful little place, it's very remote, very isolated, very private, rolling hills, it's surrounded by a farm, it's not our farm, but it's just lovely.

5
00:00:28,838 --> 00:00:30,699
We didn't tell the children we were getting it.

6
00:00:30,699 --> 00:00:44,623
It was the most magical day when we first moved in, and we were standing outside, all of us, my children, running around in the fields, they couldn't believe it, giggling, and the sun going down, and my wife and I holding hands, going, we did it, it's amazing, I'm so happy, and tears, it was beautiful.

7
00:00:44,623 --> 00:00:48,422
And lovely little animals, little birds, cos you don't see little birds in London, you know.

8
00:00:48,422 --> 00:00:56,024
In London we had pigeons, sort of suicidal pigeons, sort of come in front of the car, just look at you, kill me, end of my life, it's not worth it.

9
00:00:56,024 --> 00:01:00,324
And they just fly off at the last second, I don't even have the guts to end it!

10
00:01:00,324 --> 00:01:06,764
And all these multicoloured birds coming out of the woods, like they were welcoming us to the country, making lovely noises.

11
00:01:06,764 --> 00:01:13,099
Like they were saying, hello, welcome, thank you, thank you for coming.

12
00:01:13,099 --> 00:01:15,514
My wife holding hands, children running around, lovely.

13
00:01:15,514 --> 00:01:17,663
Then the sun went down completely.

14
00:01:17,663 --> 00:01:19,812
Absolute, total darkness.

15
00:01:19,812 --> 00:01:21,979
Pitch black, terrified.

16
00:01:21,979 --> 00:01:24,396
We both looked at where we thought we were.

17
00:01:24,396 --> 00:01:25,963
Darling, are you there? I can't even see you. "

18
00:01:25,963 --> 00:01:30,338
We should go to London, we can't do this, can we? "

19
00:01:30,338 --> 00:01:35,864
And it was like all those lovely daytime animals were instantly replaced by the night shift animals.

20
00:01:35,864 --> 00:01:39,111
Noises from birds I'd never heard before.

21
00:01:39,111 --> 00:01:44,777
Sinister sounds.

22
00:01:44,777 --> 00:01:49,266
I actually googled what bird sounds like a child screaming in the woods.

23
00:01:49,266 --> 00:01:57,836
Seriously. There was just this…

24
00:01:57,836 --> 00:02:00,725
That was it.

25
00:02:00,725 --> 00:02:11,214
My whole family holding hands in a 360, edging to where we hoped the house was.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;I want to go home!&nbsp;

26
00:02:11,214 --> 00:02:17,601
We're drifting into the neighbour's fields.&nbsp; And foxes.

27
00:02:17,601 --> 00:02:23,134
In London, when you see a fox, you see it for a second and you just go, "Oh, look, there's a fox," and then it disappears, like into thin air.

28
00:02:23,134 --> 00:02:25,534
In the country, you hear the noises they make.

29
00:02:25,534 --> 00:02:26,968
They make this vile sort of…

30
00:02:26,968 --> 00:02:31,857
Like they're vomiting violently.

31
00:02:31,857 --> 00:02:51,961
There was this fox just walking towards us. ⏩&nbsp;

32
00:02:51,961 --> 00:02:54,090
Cats. Pussycats.

33
00:02:54,090 --> 00:02:55,174
On heat.

34
00:02:55,174 --> 00:03:06,039
Is there a more sinister sound out there than a cat sort of whining?

35
00:03:06,039 --> 00:03:16,193
If only women were like this, how much easier would my teenage years have been?

36
00:03:16,193 --> 00:03:17,248
I think Beverly's up for it. "

37
00:03:17,248 --> 00:03:29,921
I think you're right, Dave, leave me to it. "&nbsp; ⏩&nbsp;

38
00:03:29,921 --> 00:03:31,323
Finally, we made it into the house.

39
00:03:31,323 --> 00:03:34,929
You know, people in the country, they say things like, "We never lock our doors in the country."

40
00:03:34,929 --> 00:03:35,342
Are you joking?

41
00:03:35,342 --> 00:03:39,296
I was putting furniture in front of the door.

42
00:03:39,296 --> 00:03:40,923
I opened the curtains to see what it was like.

43
00:03:40,923 --> 00:03:41,562
It was a fox in my face.

44
00:03:41,562 --> 00:03:45,776
Oh, my God, it's getting worse!

45
00:03:45,776 --> 00:03:49,009
Cos the fear is someone's going to break in at night.

46
00:03:49,009 --> 00:03:51,462
What are you going to do if someone breaks in in the countryside?

47
00:03:51,462 --> 00:03:58,062
In London, you tell them where you live, you tell them your road, your postcode, the number, then the police will come to your house.

48
00:03:58,062 --> 00:04:02,715
In the country, people say things like, "Ignore the postcode, that takes you to another house."

49
00:04:02,715 --> 00:04:05,979
Or, "Why don't you swap postcodes with that house?"

50
00:04:05,979 --> 00:04:09,838
Every house just has names. The Glebe House, the Rectory, the little cottage on the hill.

51
00:04:09,838 --> 00:04:11,669
I've just spent my whole life giving people directions.

52
00:04:11,669 --> 00:04:16,382
There's a dip, there's a dip in the road, you'll feel it, you won't see it, you'll feel a slight dip. "

53
00:04:16,382 --> 00:04:20,082
There's some roadkill, it used to be there, there might be some roadkill, there's a left, there's a sharp left. "

54
00:04:20,082 --> 00:04:24,249
You think you're driving into a hedge, you've got to trust it's there, you've got to trust it's there. "

55
00:04:24,249 --> 00:04:27,650
Then you'll be on a lane for about a mile, then you'll come to a huge oak tree.

56
00:04:27,650 --> 00:04:32,421
Then you know you've gone too far, you must turn back and go, "For God's sake!"

57
00:04:32,421 --> 00:04:34,867
You can't be saying this to the police on the phone.

58
00:04:34,867 --> 00:04:36,679
You might as well pass it on to the burglar.

59
00:04:36,679 --> 00:04:37,462
How did you find the place? "

60
00:04:37,462 --> 00:04:41,361
Can I put you on? "

61
00:04:41,361 --> 00:04:45,004
Because the onus is on us as men. This is what my wife does.

62
00:04:45,004 --> 00:04:47,276
Every time there's a noise in the house, she wakes me up.

63
00:04:47,276 --> 00:04:49,672
In bed, she's like, "Did you hear that?"

64
00:04:49,672 --> 00:04:51,556
Coming from the kitchen, did you hear that noise? "

65
00:04:51,556 --> 00:04:55,765
And I always deny it, even though I've heard it, because I'm awake, terrified.

66
00:04:55,765 --> 00:04:59,519
No, no, it must be the wind, even though I know there's no wind in the kitchen. "

67
00:04:59,519 --> 00:05:02,219
She always says the same thing, "Go and see."

68
00:05:02,219 --> 00:05:03,772
Go on, go downstairs and see. "

69
00:05:03,772 --> 00:05:08,057
I'm always like, "Well, that wasn't exactly the way I was going to handle this situation."

70
00:05:08,057 --> 00:05:12,000
I was hoping we would hide as a family…

71
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,671
…and await rescue. ……

72
00:05:14,671 --> 00:05:17,733
But, Michael, you're the man of the house. "

73
00:05:17,733 --> 00:05:25,929
Yes, you're right, I am the man of the house, but what concerns me at this very moment is I think there's another man in the house. "

74
00:05:25,929 --> 00:05:31,283
And I've decided to make him the man of the house on this occasion.

75
00:05:31,283 --> 00:05:32,824
But what about the children? "

76
00:05:32,824 --> 00:05:35,324
Good idea, send one of them, send the older one, the nine-year-old. "

